2015 - 2018 MLB Pitch Data Exploration¶

by Andrew Schutte¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

I found this dataset on Kaggle. It has data on every pitch thrown in the Major League Baseball regular season from 2015 to 2018. There are 4 files which I have joined together in Merge Data jupyter notebook. The data in this dataset was gather by TrackMan. For an explanation of the columns see the link:

Since there are 2.8 million(!) rows in this data set. I will only look at one pitcher's data. I will choose ZacK Greinke. He was my favorite player when we played for the Kansas City Royals. While the data from that timeframe isn't in here, it is still interesting to me. During these games he played for the Los Angels Dodgers (2015) and the Arizona Diamondbacks(2016-2018). 2015 may have been Greinke's best year as he had his lowest earned runs per 9 innings (1.66) of his career. However he only has won the Cy Young, award for the best pitcher that year, when he was with the Royals in 2009. I'm excited to analyze and visualize this data!

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset is a series of pitch information. There are measures of what the ball is doing, who is throwing it, what happened on this play, and other factors such as weather and time.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am mainly interested to see what Greinke does with each pitch. How does he attack hitters and what are his results? This can be visualized by the spin on the ball, the speed of the ball, the movement and location.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Some key variables are include: start speed, end speed, difference from start to end speed, break angle, break length, pfx_x, pfx_z, nasty, pitch type, spin rate, atbat result, pitch location/height and pitch result.

This histogram is looking at the spin rate of the pitch. Spin rates vary depending on the pitcher and pitch type. This distribution is much more smooth, but it is still not a normal distribution. We see a spike around 1800 RPM. This is a variable I will look at when looking at what affects how much a ball moves. I will keep these outliers so I can if there are any extreme effects later. I'm now going to take a look at pitch movements.

In [11]:
sb.distplot(df.pfx_x, bins = 50, kde = False)
plt.ylabel('# of pitches')
plt.xlabel('Break of the ball from release point to end point, side to side motion');

This is a weird metric. It actually looks at actual movement vs expected movement (without spin). The better the pitch, due to spin, the lower the pfx_x value. A negative value means a ball with no spin induced movement will move more. A fastball will have a higher pfx_z value because backspin will cause the ball to travel, straighter, and further and not drop as much, thus a ball with no spin would have more break. This is odd, but we will look at that later. Lets look at the pfx_z value next. (Same idea just in the vertical plane)

In [12]:
sb.distplot(df.pfx_z, bins = 50, kde = False)
plt.ylabel('# of pitches')
plt.xlabel('Break of the ball from release point to end point, low to high motion');

This variable was explained above. We will look at the relationship beyween spin rate and these values. Speaking of pitch movement, there is this cool varriable called nasty. It measures how good of a pitch is thrown. Check it out.

In [13]:
sb.distplot(df.nasty, bins = 50,  kde=False);
plt.ylabel('# of pitches');
plt.xlabel('Nasty Factor: 0-100');

This is probably my favorite variable to look at. This gives a quick summary of every pitch metric. Pitchers and hitters shouldn't go off this, but as a fan, I think it is almost the perfect introduction to these metrics. Something with a nasty factor of 100 is near unhittable. You can see Greinke has throw a few of those. Let's get back to some more complicated metrics. Break angle is up next.

In [14]:
sb.distplot(df.break_angle, bins = 50,  kde=False);
plt.ylabel('# of pitches');
plt.xlabel('Break Angle of a Pitch: 0 is where the ball traveled in a striaght line');

This is an interesting histogram. We have a negative angle on a little less then half of our pitches. I believe this is because a right handed pitcher and a left handed pitcher would have different natural movement. I will leave it as is. Here is why: Left handed pitchers will have a negative break and right handed pitchers will have a positive break, on most pitches. Using this variable, we can look at which pitches give break which is opposite of the norm for that handed of pitcher. I find it interesting how Grienke is a right handed pitcher but has a huge spike around -15 degrees. I would be willing to bet break length is some what tied to this variable. Let's look at that next.

In [15]:
sb.distplot(df.break_length, bins = 50,  kde=False);
plt.ylabel('# of pitches');
plt.xlabel('Break Length of a Pitch: 0 is where the ball traveled in a striaght line');

That looks a lot better. This measurement is in inches. The width of home plate is 17.5 inches. So this x axis looks correct. We see a large frequency of break length around 3 inches, again around 8, and 14.5. I think it will be interesting to compare the data points of pitches who have a break around 3,8, and 14.5. We also have the location of each pitch as it crosses the plate.

These distributions look the most normal. The scale is in feet. The plate is 17.5 inches wide. 0 on the x-axis is right down the middle. The height is a bit more subjective to the batter, the strike zone is relative to the player's height. However, 1.5 and 3.5 are good estimates for the bottom and top of the zone. I love to plot this and look at the location of pitches. We an look at this later. Let's look at the result of each pitch.

In [18]:
sb.catplot(data = df, x = 'code', kind = 'count', order = df.code.value_counts().index, color = 'skyblue');

The encodings are a little odd. Lucky, Kaggle has information on these values. See below:

B - Ball

*B - Ball in dirt

S - Swinging Strike

C - Called Strike

F - Foul

T - Foul Tip

L - Foul Bunt

W - Swinging Strike (Blocked)

M - Missed Bunt

P - Pitchout

Q - Swinging pitchout

R - Foul pitchout

Values that only occur on last pitch of at-bat:

X - In play, out(s)

D - In play, no out

E - In play, runs

H - Hit by pitch

I haven't been able to find what 'V' means

This is a really cool pitch by pitch result. I'd like to look into this more. These encodings are messy. Lets rename to the given definiton above.

This is a pretty cool distributions of the results of batters when they face Greinke. I told you he was a pretty good pitcher, and the most common results for batters is a strikeout. That's impressive. I want to look at the frequency of each pitch type now.

In [23]:
sb.catplot(data = df, x = 'pitch_type', kind = 'count', order = df.pitch_type.value_counts().index, color = 'skyblue');

This graph shows the amount of pitch types in our data. Here are what the variable names mean:

FF - Four-seam Fastball

SL - Slider

CH - Changeup

CU - Curveball

FT - Two-seam Fastball

EP - Eephus*

*these pitch types occur rarely,

We see that four seem fastballs and sliders are throw the most often. Greinke throws an eephus, which is an odd pitch. Here is a video. It is such a slow pitch and drops a lot. My favorite is around 40 seconds. The hitters are often completely baffled by it.

For a decent explanation of each pitch check out my blog post

Let's talk about what we see here. Some of the scatter plots show almost no correlation, but there are some indications of variables having an effect. Some plots have two or three main blows of data points. This is most likely due to the different pitch type Greinke throws. I will continue to look at different pitch types and how the metrics change.

Another observation here is that some plots have what looks like a 'V' in them. This again is most likely due to the fact that we have another variable effecting this.

Start speed, end speed, and difference all are heavily correlated. Start and end speed have the highest and most clear correlation, This shouldn't be that big of a surprise. We do have some other variables which are negatively correlated. Break_angle and pfx_x/pfx_z are negatively correlated. The higher the break angle, the lower expected movement. Break_length also had a negative correlation with start and end speed. This isn't surprising. Pitches that curve more are typically slower.

This is also a stacked bar chart, but this shows the percentages of the total.This was difficult, I used this for help. Every event length is 1, or 100%, and the length of the colored bars is the percent of each pitch per event. Here are some conclusions I came up with:

  • Greinke strikes out the most people with this four seam fastball and slider
  • He uses his change up to get ground ball outs and force outs
  • Grenike will hit batters with either his four seam or two seam fastball
  • Batters are able to hit his four seam fastball pretty well as he has given up triples the most on that pitch.
  • The eephus is not throw that often, but it is rare for a batter to hit that pitch well.

This is much better view. Here are some observations:

  • Greinke gets a lot of swing and misses on Sliders and Change Ups.
  • Greinke gets a lot of swinging strikes(blocked) or in the dirt on his Slider.
  • He also throws that pitch in the dirt a lot. This is probably a case where he hopes he can get the opponent to swing and miss at them
  • The Two Seam Fastball seems to be his worst pitch. It gets hit in play and isn't an out more often than any other type of result for that pitch.

There seems to be a strong correlation between the four seam fastballs (FF) break length and spin rate. The more it spins, the less it moves. Interesting. The eephus (EP), is the opposite. The more it spins, the less it moves. The Two Seam Fastball (FT) is similar to the FF, but it has more of a deviation. The curveball (CU) and change up (CH) have much weaker correlations.
